40abb4f7d73ceadf087e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c41ab4521c4c2b6bde7b03ec4d9531acdc101f7e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a545f286136f5024bdadaa47d305e437cf32614f.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"UI_Task,\u0022 which is depicted in a rectangular box. The flow subsequently connects to a red \u0022End\u0022 node, indicating the termination of the task sequence. In the upper right corner, there is a button labeled \u0022Task.\u0022 The overall purpose of the diagram is to outline the workflow and progression between the tasks involved in the TakeOverTasks process.\n\n\n  \n Note that a new element named  Dependencies  is created in the Model Browser. It defines the sequence in which the workflow steps are executed: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/716f7b4d18cec732881f8940608cf5835ddfdc2a.png]\nDescription: The image displays a hierarchical structure for a project labeled \u0022TakeOverTasks.\u0022 It includes sections for \u0022Context Stores\u0022 and \u0022Tasks.\u0022 Under \u0022Tasks,\u0022 there are two primary entries: \u00220100_LoadData_Task\u0022 and \u00220200_SelectionUI_Task.\u0022 The \u00220100_LoadData_Task\u0022 has expandable parameters, including \u0022DataStructure\u0022 and additional parameters. The \u00220200_SelectionUI_Task\u0022 contains a section called \u0022Dependencies,\u0022 which lists \u0022After_0100_LoadData_Task.\u0022 This structure suggests a project involving task management with dependencies and parameters for data loading and selection UI components.\n\n\n  \n To finalize this step we also need to  add checkboxes to the screen  (section) used in the workflow UI step as described  here . \n You can either do that in your standard entity screen or make a copy of it and add the  Selected  field just to it. That will make the checkboxes visible only in your workflow, not in the standard grid view of your entity. We will use the second solution here, create a  Task  screen copy named  TaskSelection  with selection boxes added. After that we also need to update the  Screen  setting in the workflow task properties and select our new screen there \u2013 in other words use our new screen in that workflow UI. \n   Step 3: Change task data \n In this step, the assignee of all selected tasks is changed to the current user. One of the Task fields is updated in the Context store for all tasks selected in the previous step. \n Create a new  (Task) Service Method Call  using the  DataTransformationService  and its  Transform  method: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f96853e5181146b9de868ed52a576c1c9084ebb5.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a service method call within a data service management system, titled \u0022(Task) Service Method Call: 0300_UpdateData_Task.\u0022 The visible sections include (Info), with subcategories such as (Schema Item), listing details like Ancestors (False) and Name (0300_UpdateData_Task). The Error Handling section specifies OnFailure as WorkflowFails. Under Misc, it includes OutputContextStore labeled as Task, OutputMethod as AppendMergeExisting, and the Service displayed as DataTransformationService with the ServiceMethod set to Transform. The Rules section consists of Features, Roles, and StartConditionRule, with some entries marked with an asterisk, indicating additional unspecified information or functionalities.\n\n\n  \n Now set up the transformation script (XSLT) that will modify the data in the Context store. \n In the Model Browser, navigate to  Business Logic / Transformations  and create a new  XSL Transformation (XSLT)  under your package. \n The transformation looks as follows: \n  \u003C?xml version=\u00221.0\u0022 encoding=\u0022UTF-8\u0022?\u003E\n\u003Cxsl:stylesheet xmlns:xsl=\u0022http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform\u0022 version=\u00221.0\u0022\n\txmlns:AS=\u0022http://schema.advantages.cz/AsapFunctions\u0022\n\txmlns:date=\u0022http://exslt.org/dates-and-times\u0022 exclude-result-prefixes=\u0022AS date\u0022\u003E\n\n\t\u003Cxsl:template match=\u0022ROOT\u0022\u003E\n\t\t\u003CROOT\u003E\n\t\t\t\u003Cxsl:apply-templates select=\u0022Task[@Selected=\u0027true\u0027]\u0022/\u003E\n\t\t\u003C/ROOT\u003E\n\t\u003C/xsl:template\u003E\n\n\t\u003Cxsl:template match=\u0022Task\u0022\u003E\n\t\t\u003Cxsl:copy\u003E\n\t\t\t\u003Cxsl:copy-of select=\u0022@*\u0022/\u003E\n\t\t\t\u003Cxsl:attribute name=\u0022refAssignedToId\u0022\u003E\n\t\t\t\t\u003Cxsl:value-of select=\u0022AS:ActiveProfileId()\u0022/\u003E\n\t\t\t\u003C/xsl:attribute\u003E\n\t\t\t\u003Cxsl:copy-of select=\u0022*\u0022/\u003E\n\t\t\u003C/xsl:copy\u003E\n\t\u003C/xsl:template\u003E\n\u003C/xsl:stylesheet\u003E\n  \n For more details, see the  tutorial related to XSL transformations . This example corresponds to the second example described there. \n Finally, reference your transformation script in the workflow step parameters. ","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-02T00:02:37"},"vector":[-0.04359439,-0.00630758,-0.071774915,-0.0045661926,0.0010050911,0.025266567,0.012251266,0.003996449,-0.0028682407,0.013496311,0.030213326,0.0017721555,0.020485327,0.016612215,0.048281778,-0.012469815,-0.00805403,0.010478523,0.03563587,0.008853661,-0.010052219,-0.03157898,-0.010114229,0.032413643,-0.00016592436,0.02552726,0.018746592,-0.027362049,-0.020551216,0.032619886,0.012060588,-0.03377672,-0.008470387,-0.019951452,-0.032867946,-0.015680833,-0.014200477,-0.005565944,-0.03918218,0.045675732,-0.009219712,-0.021644462,-0.0050479635,-0.009319722,0.058429196,-0.0261181,-0.008356081,-0.024427341,-0.012382438,-0.062158275,-0.039008472,0.0004560666,0.024784165,-0.044450033,0.03753774,0.006914345,-0.045393012,-0.037530825,-0.08890851,0.022786714,-0.063449845,0.023293372,-0.017410174,0.029